<refnamediv id='purpose'>
<refname>gimpsvg</refname>
<refpurpose>
  convert a GIMP gradient (ggr) to the SVG format.
</refpurpose>
</refnamediv>

<refsynopsisdiv id='synopsis'>
<cmdsynopsis>
  <command>gimpsvg</command>    
    <arg choice='opt'>-h </arg>
    <arg choice='opt'>-o <replaceable>file</replaceable></arg>
    <arg choice='opt'>-s <replaceable>samples</replaceable></arg>
    <arg choice='opt'>-v </arg>
    <arg choice='opt'>-V </arg>
    <arg choice='opt'><replaceable>file</replaceable></arg>
</cmdsynopsis>
</refsynopsisdiv>

<refsect1 id='description'><title>DESCRIPTION</title>
<para>
  The <command>gimpsvg</command> utility converts gradient files 
  from the 
  <citerefentry>
    <refentrytitle>GIMP</refentrytitle>
    <manvolnum>1</manvolnum>
  </citerefentry>,
  the GNU Image Manipulation Program, to the SVG (scalar 
  vector graphics) format.
</para>

<para>
  The program will read from 
  <filename moreinfo="refentry" path="/dev">stdin</filename> 
  if a file is not specified as the final argument, and write to 
  <filename moreinfo="refentry" path="/dev">stdout</filename> 
  if the <option>-o</option> option is not specified.
</para>

<para>
  The output is formatted for machines to read, rather than
  humans. A post-processor such as
  <citerefentry>
    <refentrytitle>tidy</refentrytitle>
    <manvolnum>1</manvolnum>
  </citerefentry>
  could be used in the latter case.
</para>

</refsect1>

<refsect1 id='options'><title>OPTIONS</title>
<variablelist remap='TP'>

  <varlistentry>
  <term>
  <option>-h</option>, <option>--help</option>
  </term>
  <listitem>
    <para>Brief help.</para>
  </listitem>
  </varlistentry>

  <varlistentry>
  <term>
  <option>-o</option>, <option>--output</option>
  <replaceable>file</replaceable>
  </term>
  <listitem>
  <para>Write the output to  <replaceable>file</replaceable>, 
  rather than 
  <filename moreinfo="refentry" path="/dev">stdout</filename>.
  </para>
  </listitem>
  </varlistentry>

  <varlistentry>
  <term>
  <option>-s</option>, <option>--samples</option>
  <replaceable>number</replaceable>
  </term>
  <listitem>
  <para>
    Specify the maximum <replaceable>number</replaceable> of samples. 
    <command>GIMP</command> gradients allow for complex curves in a
    number of colour-space co-ordinate systems.  In order that these 
    can be converted into SVG's simple RGB linear splines we must 
    sample these complex curves quite densely. The <option>-s</option>
    option specifies (roughly) the maximum number of samples.  In the 
    case that the GIMP gradient is an RGB linear spline gradient the 
    option has no effect, since  we can then convert the segments 
    without loss.
  </para>
  </listitem>
  </varlistentry>

  <varlistentry>
  <term>
  <option>-v</option>, <option>--verbose</option>
  </term>
  <listitem>
  <para>Verbose operation.</para>
  </listitem>
  </varlistentry>

  <varlistentry>
  <term>
  <option>-V</option>, <option>--version</option>
  </term>
  <listitem>
  <para>Version information.</para>
  </listitem>
  </varlistentry>

</variablelist>
</refsect1>

<refsect1 id='files'><title>FILES</title>

<para>
  The <command>gimpsvg</command> program will search for 
  gradient files 
</para>

<itemizedlist mark="dash">

  <listitem>
    <para>
      in the directories specified in <envar>GIMP_GRADIENTS</envar>;
    </para>
  </listitem>

  <listitem>
    <para>
      in the user's GIMP directory,
      <envar
	  >HOME</envar><filename class="directory"
	  >/.gimp-<replaceable
	  >version</replaceable>/gradients</filename>;
    </para>
  </listitem>

  <listitem>
    <para>	
      in the standard locations
      <filename class="directory"
		>/usr/share/gimp/<replaceable
		>version</replaceable>/gradients</filename>
      and 
      <filename class="directory"
		>/usr/share/local/gimp/<replaceable
		>version</replaceable>/gradients</filename>,
    </para>
  </listitem>

</itemizedlist>
  
<para>
  where <replaceable>version</replaceable> ranges over 
  feasible version numbers.
</para>

</refsect1>

<refsect1 id='environment'><title>ENVIRONMENT</title>
<para>
  If the <envar>GIMP_GRADIENTS</envar> variable is defined then
  each colon-separated directory therein will be searched for
  gradient files.
</para>
</refsect1>

